translated: Bensow, Bror Folke, architect, Gothenburg, born on February 19, 1886 in Gothenburg, son of dentist Jakob Victor B. O'. Sigrid Maria. Married to Jenny Vogel in 1924, with one child named Eva, born in 1924. He passed the student examination in natural science in Gothenburg in 1904, and graduated from the Royal Institute of Technology in Stockholm in 1909. He studied at the Academy of Fine Arts in Copenhagen from 1910-1911 and graduated from the Royal Academy of Fine Arts in Stockholm in 1912. He traveled to Germany and Austria in 1910, and to Italy, Greece, and Egypt in 1921-1922. He was a second lieutenant in the Skaraborg Regiment in 1906, became lieutenant in 1913, and captain in 1926. He worked as an architect in Stockholm from 1915-1930 and as a property manager for Pripp & Lyckholm in Gothenburg from 1931. Among his works are Laxholmsväveriet in Norrköping, the bachelor hotel Gothia in Gothenburg, the restoration of Hjulsta corps de logis in Uppland, Pripp's restaurant at the jubilee exhibition in Gothenburg, Snäckgärdsbaden's hotel and restaurant in Visby, a carbon dioxide factory in Sävenäs, and a water factory in Gothenburg. His hobby was painting. He was a member of the Swedish Engineering Association since 1915.
